  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div slot="faq" class="space-y-6">
    <details class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-lg cursor-pointer">When should my child first see a dentist?</summary>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600">
        The Canadian Dental Association recommends children visit the dentist by their first birthday 
        or within 6 months of their first tooth appearing. Early visits help establish good habits 
        and allow us to catch any issues early.
      </p>
    </details>
    
    <details class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-lg cursor-pointer">How can I prepare my child for their dental visit?</summary>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600">
        Keep it positive! Read books about dental visits, play "dentist" at home, and avoid using 
        scary words. Let us know if your child has any special needs or anxieties so we can make 
        extra accommodations.
      </p>
    </details>
    
    <details class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-lg cursor-pointer">Are dental X-rays safe for children?</summary>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600">
        Yes! We use digital X-rays which emit 90% less radiation than traditional film X-rays. 
        We only take X-rays when necessary and use protective lead aprons. The diagnostic benefits 
        far outweigh the minimal risks.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-lg cursor-pointer">What if my child is afraid of the dentist?</summary>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600">
        Dental anxiety is common and we're experienced in helping fearful children. We use gentle 
        techniques, go at your child's pace, and offer comfort options like nitrous oxide. Many 
        anxious children become our happiest patients!
      </p>
    </details>
  </div>

